Final Project: UFO Sightings & U.S. Air Quality

Alyssa Knapp

12/13/20

Link to GitHub

https://github.com/alyssaknapp/Final-Project-UFO-sightings-US-Air-Quality

Research Question

Where are UFO sightings in the United States associated with pollutant levels of carbon monoxide (CO) and nitrogen dioxide (NO2) and how do these levels change over time?

Purpose

This topic is important to investigate because there is currently very little knowledge of how climate information relates to UFO sightings. Air quality, in particular, is interesting to explore because air pollutants, such as NO2 and CO, can impair visibility, which may affect the ability of UFOs to be seen in the sky. This relationship is expected to become more polarized over time, as air quality worsens.

Variables To Be Used (originally included in data sets)

Data Set 1: Country (will limit to only include USA), State (records data from certain states)

Data Set 2: State (records data from certain states), Month (all 12 months), Year (contains data from 2000 to 2008)

  • NO2/CO Mean: mean concentration within a given day
  • NO2/CO AQI: Air quality index within a given day
  • NO2/CO 1st Max Value: maximum value obtained within a given day
  • NO2/CO 1st Max Hour: the hour when the maximum concentration was obtained
  • ET: equal to 1 if a UFO was sighted, 0 otherwise (binary)

Joining Data Sets & Creating Data Frames

Join <- left_join(UFO_US %>% 
                    group_by(State) %>% 
                    mutate(id = row_number()), 
                    AirQ_long %>% 
                    group_by(state) %>% 
                    mutate(id = row_number()), 
                    by = c("State" = "state", "id"))

  Join %>%
  select(Country, State, Region, day, month, year, hour, ET, date_time, weekday, pollutants, value)

Conclusions

Due to wrangling my data and creating visualizations, I was able to explore the relationship between the four air pollutants (NO2.Mean, NO2.AQI, CO.Mean, and CO.AQI) and UFO sightings, in terms of their location in the United States and the time recorded. U.S. location was measured at the region and state level, while time was measured in terms of hours in a day, weekdays, months and years (from 2000-2008).

Regions: For NO2.AQI and NO2.Mean, I found that the West and Northeast regions were associated with the highest pollutant levels and UFO sightings, followed by the South and Midwest regions. For CO.AQI and CO.Mean, an association between UFO sightings and U.S. regions was difficult to determine due to the smaller number of cases recorded. However, these pollutants were technically highest in the West region and lowest in the Northeast region. Overall, the West region showed the greatest association between air pollutants and UFO sightings.

States: I found that NO2 pollutants, associated with UFO sightings, were highest in California (CA) and lowest in Tennessee (TN). In contrast, CO pollutants, associated with UFO sightings, were highest in Florida and lowest in Kansas (KS). Given these findings, I can conclude that there is no obvious trend or pattern with regard to state. Some possible patterns could have shown high pollutant levels and UFO sightings in adjacent states or states with warmer temperatures.

Hours: I found that NO2.AQI and NO2.Mean pollutant levels, associated with UFO sightings, generally increased in the early hours of a given day, decreased midday, and then increased again in the late hours of the day. In contrast, CO.AQI remained relatively constant over the hours of a given day, while CO.Mean increased until the 10-hour mark then decreased until the 20-hour mark before increasing again. Therefore, it can be concluded that NO2.AQI, NO2.Mean, and CO.Mean fluctuated (increasing and decreasing) throughout the hours of a given day, while CO.AQI stayed constant.

Weekdays: I found that NO2.AQI pollutant levels, associated with UFO sightings, increased until Thursday, decreased until Saturday, then increased on Sunday. In contrast, NO2.Mean, CO.AQI, and CO.Mean pollutant levels, associated with UFO sightings, remained relatively constant throughout the weekdays.

Months: I found that NO2 pollutants and CO.Mean,associated with UFO sightings, started at high levels before decreasing, then increasing again. However, CO.AQI stayed fairly constant throughout the months.

Years: I found that both NO2.AQI and CO.Mean, associated with UFO sightings, were highest in 2006 and lowest in 2008. However, NO2.Mean, associated with UFO sightings, was highest in 2004 and lowest in 2000 and 2007. CO.AQI, associated with UFO sightings, was also highest in 2007 and lowest in 2003 and 2004. This showed that throughout the years, when NO2.Mean was highest, CO.AQI was typically lowest. Moreover, although NO2.AQI and CO.AQI showed higher averages over the years, NO2.Mean and CO.Mean ultimately showed higher pollutant levels, associated with UFO sightings.

Based on my time results, I can conclude that CO.AQI pollutant levels remained relatively constant over time, while the NO2 pollutants and CO.Mean fluctuated over time and peaked in different years. Altogether, NO2.Mean showed the highest pollutant levels, associated with UFO sightings, over the years.

Overall, my findings show some variation and pose additional questions, so I believe more research should be conducted on this topic. Additional research would offer more information about the potential relationship between air pollutants, UFO sightings, U.S. location, and time.
